@3400 = ~Peace of the Goddess be upon you. It is rare for strangers to find their way here. This grove reveals itself only to those who already know of it.~
@3401 = ~How is it, then, that you have come—and that Eldath has allowed your steps to pass?~
@3402 = ~A follower of your faith was poisoned. I bring an arrow—perhaps your leader can trace its source.~
@3403 = ~Some poison, people dying... I don’t have time for pleasantries. Just point me to the high priest.~
@3404 = ~Honestly? One of yours is dead, and now I’m the one cleaning up the mess because you're all too weak to act. Where’s your spineless leader hiding?~
@3405 = ~I'm looking for the Most Exhausted Fallseater Alley-toes Berendish.~
@3406 = ~I'm looking for the Most Exalted Fallskeeper Alatoasz Berendim.~
@3407 = ~By the Mother Guardian of Groves! Then Merethan has fallen? It is him you speak of, yes? This is grave news indeed...~
@3408 = ~Quickly—bring the poisoned arrow to our High Priest. You’ll find him in his chambers, in the rearmost northeastern tree by the water’s edge. But be careful—the venom seems potent, and even a trace may do harm. Alatoasz will know how to proceed.~
@3409 = ~Despite these troubling times, I bid you welcome to our grove. May the Green Goddess grant you her blessing.~
@3410 = ~You'll find him in his chambers, in the rearmost tree by the water. Now go—and trouble others no more.~
@3411 = ~I believe you’re referring to the Most Exalted Fallskeeper Alatoasz Berendim. Peace teaches us patience, but even names deserve respect. He resides in the treehouse by the water, northeast of here.~
@3412 = ~You’ll find our High Priest in his chambers, in the northeastern tree at the water’s edge. May he grant you the Green Goddess’s blessing.~
@3413 = ~May the Mother Guardian of Groves grant you peace and health, stranger. I am Most Exalted Fallskeeper Alatoasz Berendim, a humble servant of Eldath. What brings you to our sanctuary?~
@3414 = ~Let's make it brief: Merethan is dead. He was killed with this poison. We need to find out who made it.~
@3415 = ~Your priest, Merethan, was poisoned. I have here an arrow soaked in the toxin. He hoped you might be able to use it to trace the culprit.~
@3416 = ~Merethan died choking on his peace. This poisoned arrow’s all that’s left.~
@3417 = ~Greetings, Most Exalted Fallskeeper. I bring sad news—your priest Merethan was poisoned. This arrow carries the same toxin that killed him... and others. Merethan hoped you could trace its source.~
@3418 = ~I'm looking for the Moist Exulted Flailweeper Appletoast Barelydim.~
@3419 = ~Blast it! You’ve seen through my disguise! I’m not Alatoasz at all... I'm Appletoast! A pity... I worked hard on the beard and the title. Would you still care to talk to this imposter, or shall I bow out and leave you to your heroic wandering?~
@3420 = ~This is sad news. Merethan was a faithful follower—a Freewalker—traveling to spread the word of peace throughout the Realms. It pains me that he has left our world. I know the circumstances—indeed, I was the one who tasked him with investigating the troubling cases of poisoning.~
@3421 = ~Let me take a closer look at the arrow...~
@3422 = ~A strange poison indeed. Merethan must have told you what makes this toxin so troubling?~
@3423 = ~More or less.~
@3424 = ~I prefered you reminded me why it scares you so much.~
@3425 = ~He said it couldn’t be cured.~
@3426 = ~Neither magic nor simple antidotes are swift enough to rid the body of this toxin. All our prayers, all our powers—none can turn back its corruption.~
@3427 = ~Yet there is hope. Despite these grim circumstances, it is a blessing that you have brought me a sample of this vile substance.~
@3428 = ~Exactly. Despite the grim circumstances, it is fortunate that you brought me a sample of this vile substance.~
@3429 = ~Let me cast a spell to better understand the nature of the poison...~
@3430 = ~Even a divination spell fails? How can that be...?~
@3431 = ~Well then, if magic fails, we must rely on our senses. I smell something on this arrow—a peculiar scent, sharp and sweet. A plant-based poison, for sure...~
@3432 = ~Let me taste a small amount of the poison.~
@3433 = ~You’re not seriously putting that in your mouth, are you?~
@3434 = ~Careful! I don’t want to lose a second Eldathyn.~
@3435 = ~If tasting it brings us answers, then so be it.~
@3436 = ~Use at your own risk.~
@3437 = ~I know the risk, but we have no time. If this toxin spreads to even more dangerous hands, the cost will be far greater.~
@3438 = ~Hmm... The taste is like the nectar of a flower long forgotten—sweet, yet slipping through memory like petals on the wind. The scent lingers like overripe fruit in a sun-dappled grove, fragrant one moment, lost the next.~
@3439 = ~There is a bitterness, like foxglove, but something older lingers within it... something raw and untamed. The numbness spreads, slow and deliberate, reaching toward my heart. Could it be—~
@3440 = ~Of course! It must be the Groveglove—a rare elven plant! Highly toxic and revered by elves for millennia.~
@3441 = ~Yet its poison is usually easily cured by magic—so why does it fail now? It makes no sense.~
@3442 = ~Good thing that stuff didn’t kill you too.~
@3443 = ~You seem to place a lot of trust in the protection of your goddess. Don't overdo it.~
@3444 = ~And you figured all that out by sniffing the arrow and tasting the poison?~
@3445 = ~We often deal with poisons here. Many gravely ill souls come to us, and it falls to us to either heal them or guide them through death. Over time, we’ve gained unfortunate familiarity with some of the foulest substances in the Realms. But never have I encountered something like this. Well, no matter. For now, we know where our search must begin.~
@3446 = ~The plant used to create this poison grows near the ruins of ancient elven cities, where the land still remembers its old magic. That must be where the poison is being produced. We need to focus on one of the old elven ruins scattered throughout these lands. But there are many. Finding the right one will be our first task.~
@3447 = ~How many possible ancient elven ruins are we talking about?~
@3448 = ~Elven cities, old magic, mysterious poison plants—this keeps getting better and better.~
@3449 = ~Your knowledge is impressive.~
@3450 = ~This region, as you may know, was once blanketed by a vast and unbroken forest—the ancient heart of the elven kingdom of Keltormir. The elves built many splendid cities within those woods, and though their time has passed, ruins remain... and so do rare plants. Plants that may lead us to the right place.~
@3451 = ~Keltormir? Sure, Candlekeep had stuff on it. All leaves and legends. Elves love their trees, don’t they?~
@3452 = ~The tale of Keltormir is well known among my people. It is our lost heritage... but all that remains are memories.~
@3453 = ~I believe I've come across the name Keltormir in my studies. Familiar... but long vanished.~
@3454 = ~And where should I begin the search?~
@3455 = ~Time to uncover what’s left of Keltormir.~
@3456 = ~Unfortunately, I am no scholar of ancient history. My expertise lies in nature. But fortunately, I know someone who is.~
@3457 = ~I ask you to visit the Temple of Oghma in Athkatla. They keep many ancient tomes there, including some that speak of the old elven cities. If I can obtain even a single clue, I may be able to narrow our search considerably.~
@3458 = ~Back to Athkatla, then.~
@3459 = ~I just arrived here from Athkatla, and you're already sending me back?~
@3460 = ~I don’t usually run errands for books... but fine.~
@3461 = ~If you say it helps, I’ll fetch your book.~
@3462 = ~What about Suldanesselar? Perhaps we should seek answers there?~
@3463 = ~I have already been to Myth Rhynn, searching for the ancient prophecies of Calim and Memnon. Perhaps that is where we should begin our search?~
@3464 = ~Suldanesselar? I know the place. They have many troubles, but none that connect to ours.~
@3465 = ~Myth Rhynn, the elven city of the dead? No, I do not believe our answers lie there.~
@3466 = ~There’s no way around it—you must seek the Temple of Oghma in Athkatla. They keep many tomes, including some that speak of the old elven cities. If I can find even a single clue, I may be able to narrow our search considerably.~
@3467 = ~I just came from Athkatla, and now you’re sending me back?~
@3468 = ~If you think it’ll help, I’ll fetch your book.~
@3469 = ~In the meantime, I shall reflect further on the nature of this poison. You were kind enough to bring me a sample... though it came at the cost of a good priest’s life.~
@3470 = ~I’ll be on my way, then.~
@3471 = ~One more thing—I have Merethan’s symbol of Eldath with me.~
@3472 = ~Such emblems are usually passed from one priest to another. Yet for now, I know no one who should carry it. Keep it with you for the time being—mayhap we shall find a worthy soul to whom it may be entrusted.~
@3473 = ~I might know someone—Montrassa, the elderly priestess. Her hands have grown too frail to craft her own emblem.~
@3474 = ~Montrassa? She never spoke of such difficulty... but it makes perfect sense. A thoughtful suggestion! Give her the emblem, with my blessing. And afterward, please proceed to the Temple of Oghma in Athkatla, as we discussed.~
@3475 = ~I shall send a dove ahead to the Temple of Oghma, so their scribes may ready the proper volume. Return to me once you have the book. I shall be waiting below, on the lower level of this tree. May Eldath's blessings guide your steps.~
@3476 = ~<CHARNAME>! You have returned. Have you brought the book from the Temple of Oghma?~
@3477 = ~Yes, here it is.~
@3478 = ~Give me another moment. I’ll get back to you as soon as I can.~
@3479 = ~Such emblems are usually passed from one priest to another. Yet at this moment, I know no one to whom it should be given. Hold onto it for now—perhaps we shall find a fitting bearer.~
@3480 = ~I believe I know someone—Montrassa, the elderly priestess, whose hands can no longer craft her own.~
@3481 = ~Montrassa? She never spoke of such a hardship, but... yes. It is a sound suggestion. Give her the emblem with my blessing.~
@3482 = ~I shall be honored to deliver your blessing to her.~
@3483 = ~Do so. She will surely be uplifted by your kindness.~
@3484 = ~Interesting... A well-crafted tome, with valuable insights. Three Mythal-cities are mentioned explicitly here: Myth Rhynn, Myth Unnohyr, and Myth Tellaren. Hmm. Oh! This is promising—mayhap even a true lead.~
@3485 = ~Of the three cities, which calls to you as the source? Where do you feel the trail leads?~
@3486 = ~Myth Rhynn.~
@3487 = ~Myth Unnohyr.~
@3488 = ~Myth Tellaren.~
@3489 = ~I’m not sure.~
@3490 = ~I’ve only examined the book’s cover.~
@3491 = ~I don’t read stupid books.~
@3492 = ~Myth Rhynn—the elven necropolis? An intriguing thought, but no... I don’t believe that’s where we’ll find our answer.~
@3493 = ~Maybe Myth Tellaren?~
@3494 = ~Then it must be Myth Unnohyr.~
@3495 = ~Myth Tellaren, buried in the sands of Calimshan? We’ll not find a single living plant there—certainly not the one we’re seeking. I’m afraid that can’t be it.~
@3496 = ~Myth Rhynn?~
@3497 = ~Then Myth Unnohyr must be the one.~
@3498 = ~It's Myth Unnohyr! That must be the place. Listen to this passage: 'When his blessing was withdrawn, the mythal shattered in silent judgment, leaving behind a zone of wild and dead magic—a festering wound in the Weave that endures to this day. Now, few dare to approach its ruins, where even divine power falters, and plants whisper poison into the soil.'~
@3499 = ~That explains why our attempts at healing fail — the plant used to brew this incurable poison grows in the soil of a corrupted Mythal. It draws dead magic into itself and spreads that very rot through the victim’s body as venom. And all of this fits perfectly with what we know of Myth Unnohyr.~
@3500 = ~If you say so.~
@3501 = ~If that’s where the plant grows, that’s where we’ll go.~
@3502 = ~Not exactly a pleasant destination.~
@3503 = ~You mean the plant feeds on dead magic? Wicked.~
@3504 = ~I'll wait here, then.~
@3505 = ~Myth Unnohyr seems to have once been a glorious, mythal-shrouded elven city. But one day, a mysterious catastrophe caused that mythal to implode, leaving behind a vast magical abomination: A wild magic zone by day and a dead magic zone by night.~
@3506 = ~Wild magic?! Gods, yes! Or no. Or maybe! I love it when even reality can’t make up its mind.~
@3507 = ~Elven ruins or not, this mythal was never meant for mortal hands. And now it bleeds its vengeance into the land.~
@3508 = ~Creepy ruins, cursed mythals, shattered relics—these elves had a real flair for drama.~
@3509 = ~When gods fall silent, the poison sings.~
@3510 = ~Magic there seems to be highly unstable—at least the kind that relies on spellcraft. Whether innate gifts or enchanted items still function, I cannot say.~
@3511 = ~And you want me to go there?~
@3512 = ~So we’ll have to rely on steel and wits.~
@3513 = ~I suppose I fight the battles while you stay clean and speak of stillness?~
@3514 = ~Easy to preach peace from the safety of a grove, while I wade through blood in your name.~
@3515 = ~Magic or no magic, death still listens when I speak.~
@3516 = ~I am no warrior—only a voice that tries to guide the blade toward mercy. Do not mistake stillness for blindness. I know what I ask of you, and I do not ask it lightly. But even the dirtiest task can plant a seed. Let us hope something better grows from it.~
@3517 = ~The poisonous plant must grow there—twisted by wild magic and infused with death magic. Its venom carries that same warped magic into the body of its victims.~
@3518 = ~That’s an interesting theory.~
@3519 = ~Alright. To cure the victims, we’d have to cure the magic itself—or what’s left of it.~
@3520 = ~Then we’ve half-solved the problem already.~
@3521 = ~The only remaining question is who is crafting the poison. Did you catch a glimpse of Merethan’s killer?~
@3522 = ~Not really. He said something like Mal... Malar...~
@3523 = ~Couldn't you have asked me that earlier? Now I’ve forgotten it again.~
@3524 = ~Strange fellow with a strange name. Something like Mala-something.~
@3525 = ~He called himself Malagent.~
@3526 = ~Think back. Did he give you any name that might help us?~
@3527 = ~Malagent?~
@3528 = ~Yes, that must be it.~
@3529 = ~Maybe?~
@3530 = ~I don't know and I don't care.~
@3531 = ~A Malagent! That fits perfectly. That’s what the unholy agents of Talona call themselves—poisoners, corrupters, bringers of decay. Do you know who Talona is?~
@3532 = ~Yes.~
@3533 = ~No.~
@3534 = ~Talona is the Lady of Poison and Mistress of Disease. Her followers wander the world spreading suffering and decay—why not with a newly brewed poison? Her devotees are quite... inventive.~
@3535 = ~Then it all makes sense. The incurable poison, the corrupted magic... it all bears Talona's mark. We now know that our enemy serves none other than the Lady of Poisons herself. This Malagent is working as her hand, spreading poison everywhere. We have the answers. Now we seek the source.~
@3536 = ~Let me guess—I get to face the poisoned arrows and monsters and traps, and you get to write a prayer about it.~
@3537 = ~His poison lingers. So will our blade.~
@3538 = ~Then let’s not waste time.~
@3539 = ~The path is clear. Faith and steel shall see us through.~
@3540 = ~Fine. But I expect at least one uneventful day after this.~
@3541 = ~Seeking answer’s the easy part. What comes after tends to get messy.~
@3542 = ~One question, though... are any fights allowed under Eldath’s rules? Or is all violence forbidden?~
@3543 = ~Some things have strayed too far from nature's balance, there are afflictions no prayer can cleanse, only removal will suffice.~
@3544 = ~Undead, for example. They are a distortion of the natural cycle. They cling to suffering and bring only more of it.~
@3545 = ~Some beings are twisted by foul magic—poisoned roots, cursed beasts, unholy revenants. If they cannot be saved... they must be stilled.~
@3546 = ~To protect life from such corruption is not to betray peace. But violence must always be the last word, not the first.~
@3547 = ~Seems even your goddess allows for a bit of bloodshed when things go bad.~
@3548 = ~Phew. For a moment, I thought I'd have to hug a ghoul.~
@3549 = ~Great news. I'd hate to throw all my weapons into a pond.~
@3550 = ~So I can still defend myself, if it’s truly needed. I’ll take that.~
@3551 = ~I can live with that. Peace when possible, power when required.~
@3552 = ~That’s all I needed to know.~
@3553 = ~Eldath has shown you the path—now you must walk it on your own.~
@3554 = ~In Myth Unnohyr you will find both the plant and the culprit. But it will not be easy—I dare not imagine what other creatures might dwell in such a forsaken place. You’ll find the ruins of Myth Unnohyr in the southern remnants of the ancient elven forests. I’ll mark the location on your map.~
@3555 = ~The weak weep for balance. The strong thrive in chaos. I say let this Mythal rot—it is not our concern.~
@3556 = ~Evil magic in the air? Boo says it feels like we should hit something until it’s peaceful again!~
@3557 = ~The poisoner has made his mark. Now let nature guide our retribution.~
@3558 = ~Such defilement is a blight upon the realms. It offends all that is sacred. It must be ended.~
@3559 = ~May our steps disturb not the ruins, but leave a mark where balance must be restored.~
@3560 = ~Please, let’s be careful. I fear whatever broke the Mythal still lingers—and it doesn’t welcome visitors.~
@3561 = ~One more thing: Should you come across the flower he twisted to his ends, bring it to me. I shall seek to cleanse it and create an antidote.~
@3562 = ~Go now, and put an end to the servant of Talona. May the blessings of Eldath guide your next steps.~
@3563 = ~You have returned! Have you found the one behind the poison and brought him to justice?~
@3564 = ~The Malagent is dead.~
@3565 = ~I have nothing to report yet.~
@3566 = ~One thing keeps bugging me: Are there any creatures I'm actually allowed to fight in your name?~
@3567 = ~We do not seek battle—but there are things that no longer belong in this world.~
@3568 = ~Seems even your goddess allows for a bit of steel when things go bad.~
@3569 = ~You know best how to proceed. I shall wait here for your return.~
@3570 = ~That is heartening news! Though I am no friend to violence, at times it is better that a wrongdoer troubles another realm rather than this one.~
@3571 = ~You are most deserving of a reward for what you have done—for us, for Amn, and for all who might have fallen prey to that vile toxin. Here, I have gathered as much gold as I could for you.~
@3572 = ~You have rendered us a great service, and for that I thank you! Yet the matter may still be set to greater rights.~
@3573 = ~With the proper antidote, we could nullify all the poisons this venom-brewer has already loosed upon the land. But to craft it, we require a sample of the plant the Malagent used for his foul draughts. Were you able to secure a specimen of Groveglove?~
@3574 = ~I have brought you a specimen of that plant.~
@3575 = ~Would this little flower be the one you seek?~
@3576 = ~I have not yet come across such a plant.~
@3577 = ~I am weary and would rest now. Let us speak of this another time.~
@3578 = ~So, you have it! That is most welcome news.~
@3579 = ~I see. Then I can only ask that you search once more within the ruins of Myth Unnohyr for this plant. Return to me when you have secured the specimen.~
@3580 = ~Ah, you’ve returned! I trust this means you're still invested in our cause. Though the main threat has been dealt with, our task is not yet complete.~
@3581 = ~We spoke of the flower before—do you recall? That is what I wish to discuss now.~
@3582 = ~Before your journey to Myth Unnohyr, I asked you to search for the plant our enemy used to brew the poison.~
@3583 = ~Though the source has been silenced, I fear the poison is already out there in the Realms—passed from hand to hand, vial to vial. I wish to craft an antidote, and I hope you will aid me in this final step.~
@3584 = ~But knowledge alone won’t suffice. First, we need the flower itself. Have you brought it?~
@3585 = ~Yes. It is here.~
@3586 = ~I’m afraid not.~
@3587 = ~I’m glad you’re here. Have you found the flower?~
@3588 = ~Yes, I have it with me.~
@3589 = ~No, not yet.~
@3590 = ~Give me a moment. I’ll be back shortly.~
@3591 = ~You don’t have it? That is most unfortunate.~
@3592 = ~If we are to prepare the antidote, the flower is essential. Please, continue your search. I shall remain here and wait. May Eldath guide your steps.~
@3593 = ~Let me take a look at the plant. Keep it with you, however, for you shall soon have need of it. So, this is the Groveglove—grown in a dead-magic zone within Myth Unnohyr. How very curious...~
@3594 = ~It is in fine condition, yes. And it has grown tall, laden with venomous blossoms—more than enough for an antidote!~
@3595 = ~While you strove to thwart our foe, I believe I have found a way to fashion such an antidote. For it, we require both the flower and knowledge of the precise place—the cauldron or laboratory—where the poison was first brewed.~
@3596 = ~I recall the place well. A cauldron, steeped in the venom of his craft.~
@3597 = ~I did notice a cauldron there, though I had little mind for it while trading blows.~
@3598 = ~Oh, that bubbling pot? Looked like something half-finished—and wholly unpleasant.~
@3599 = ~That is precisely what I had hoped. Yet more is still required. Allow me to share what I discovered.~
@3600 = ~Know this: Three blessings of the gods must be inscribed upon this flower. One or two alone shall not avail, for the dead magic that has fed it is grievously strong. Only when it is sanctified with life, compassion, and renewal may the corruption be purged.~
@3601 = ~I cannot bestow all three blessings myself. For this, we must seek the aid of other faiths. And I know well where to turn for such help.~
@3602 = ~You must travel to Athkatla and speak with the priest of Ilmater in the Slums. Ask him for the Blessing of Compassion. He and I are on good terms—I believe he will support our cause without hesitation.~
@3603 = ~You should also visit the Church of Lathander in the city and request the Blessing of Renewal. I shall send a white dove ahead with my message. By the time you arrive, they will already be prepared to aid you.~
@3604 = ~Compassion? Renewal? Sounds like a feast fer cowards.~
@3605 = ~Oh splendid. A holy scavenger hunt. Shall we embroider the petals with lace as well?~
@3606 = ~Renewal? Life? You would have us grovel before Ilmater’s sniveling flock? The weak cling to such words when truth and strength fail them.~
@3607 = ~Compassion is for the meek. Renewal is for the broken. Neither are for me.~
@3608 = ~If I wanted sermons, I would have stayed in Thay—at least there they come with necromancy and a sacrifice.~
@3609 = ~As for the third part, I shall bestow upon you the Blessing of Life myself.~
@3610 = ~Done. These blessings should rest upon you as well, so that should the flower resist even prayer, your own hands may yet bear the grace to pass them on.~
@3611 = ~The Morninglord’s servant stands before you; permit me to bless the flower.~
@3612 = ~What about me? Perhaps I should bless the flower, too? I am also a person of faith!~
@3613 = ~Very well. Once the blessings are gathered, I shall return to you without delay.~
@3614 = ~I will do as you ask, though it seems no simple errand.~
@3615 = ~If the gods themselves are to be invoked, I can only hope the reward proves as divine as the task.~
@3616 = ~I trust there will be due reward for all the effort and time this task demands of me?~
@3617 = ~Ah, I had not considered that—of course! Very well, then. Proceed, and lay your blessing upon it.~
@3618 = ~I remain certain that these priests must aid us—I have already sent letters, and they will be expecting you. Yet your blessing, too, may lend strength to our cause.~
@3619 = ~While I do like you, there is this dark part in you. I am sorry, but we need something else than this. But I do appreciate your offer.~
@3620 = ~Thank you. Yet remember, we shall need the blessings of all faiths I spoke of.~
@3621 = ~Of course. I'll prepare something for you. Not gold, but something else. Something that will be of use during your journeys.~
@3622 = ~In addition, you will need a jug of Eldath’s holy water from our grotto. Speak to Eldath’s handmaiden near the water; she will give you a carafe of the sacred water.~
@3623 = ~When you have the water and the blessings of Lathander and Ilmater, return to me. Then I shall tell you what must be done next.~
@3624 = ~I'm counting on you, <CHARNAME>. We will be able to halt the spread of this vile poison — of that I am certain. Return to me once you have gathered everything.~
@3625 = ~I was sent here from Duskwood Dell. I have this flower and I need a Blessing of Compassion. I believe you may have already received a letter describing the details.~
@3626 = ~Ah… yes. I had thought they would send one of their own, yet it matters not. You have come, and you shall not be denied my blessing.~
@3627 = ~Hear me, Ilmater, Crying God, Endurer of all torments. Look with pity upon those who suffer and grant them the strength to endure. Let their burdens be eased, if only for a moment, and let their pain be mine to bear. Weep for the wounded, shield the broken, and clothe us all in patience and mercy. In your compassion lies our only hope—so let that hope flow now into this flower, that it may carry solace where poison once was sown.~
@3628 = ~The blessing is given. Take it, my child, and let your heart weep for others, as my god has ever wept for you.~
@3629 = ~I was sent here from Duskwood Dell. I have this flower and I need a Blessing of Renewal. I believe you may have already received a letter describing the details.~
@3630 = ~Yes, yes—I did receive the letter, and of course I shall grant you my blessing, that you may continue your quest with the Morninglord’s light at your side.~
@3631 = ~Lathander, Bringer of the Dawn, Herald of Renewal, grant this <PRO_RACE> your blessing. Fill <PRO_HIMHER> with the warmth of the rising sun, that <PRO_HESHE> may carry its light even into the coldest shadows and darkest dens.~
@3632 = ~The blessing is bestowed. Go now with the Morninglord’s light upon you—may his dawn ever rise within your heart, and may each step you take carry the promise of renewal.~
@3633 = ~Welcome back. Have you received the blessings already and gathered some of Eldath's holy water from our grotto?~
@3634 = ~Yes, I have. What's next?~
@3635 = ~I'm still working on this.~
@3636 = ~I see. Return to me when you're done with that part. Eldath bless you!~
@3637 = ~We have the flower, the holy water of Eldath, and we have the blessings. And we know where the poison was prepared.~
@3638 = ~You must return to Myth Unnohyr and place the blessed flower together with Eldath’s holy water within the Malagent’s cauldron. But beware—this may stir an unwelcome reaction, and you may be forced to defend yourself.~
@3639 = ~Then let the vile concoction be given flesh, that we might smite it in righteous combat!~
@3640 = ~This is either going to end in glorious salvation... or one really big kaboom.~
@3641 = ~So, we toss blessings in, stir thrice clockwise, and hope it doesn’t explode in our faces? Sounds like my first cooking attempts with Winthrop back in Candlekeep.~
@3642 = ~If the cauldron brews a monster, then we make chopped monster stew! Justice will be well-fed today!~
@3643 = ~If it starts sprouting tentacles, just remember: Tentacles first, clean-up later. Worked for Aunt Belba’s laundry cauldron.~
@3644 = ~Return to me with the completed antidote, and you shall have both my gratitude and a fitting reward. May Eldath’s peace enfold you on your path and may shield you from all harm until we meet again.~
@3645 = ~Have you fashioned the antidote? Is that why you have returned—to bring me good news?~
@3646 = ~Yes. Here it is. May it spare many lives.~
@3647 = ~Here—freshly wrought, and hard-won.~
@3648 = ~This vial cost me blood, sweat, and a few corpses.~
@3649 = ~Not yet.~
@3650 = ~I understand. Return to me as soon as it is complete. This is of great import, and we are close now.~
@3651 = ~Oh, blessed day! You have done a deed of true compassion. Few could be called a greater friend to peace than you.~
@3652 = ~With this antidote, we shall answer whenever word reaches us of one stricken by a poison or ailment untouched by magic. Through it, lives will be spared, and suffering eased.~
@3653 = ~For all you have done—for the people of Amn, and for Duskwood Dell—I offer my deepest thanks. And as I promised, I have something for you. May it aid you in the trials and journeys yet before you.~
@3654 = ~And know this: Whenever you are in need of shelter or rest, Duskwood Dell shall welcome you with open arms, under the peace of Eldath’s embrace.~
@3655 = ~It gladdens me to see you again, <CHARNAME>. As I have said before, Duskwood Dell shall ever welcome you in peace.~
@3656 = ~Thank you, I appreciate that.~
@3657 = ~I must be going.~
@3658 = ~Montrassa? She never spoke of such hardship, but... yes. It is a sound suggestion. Give her the emblem with my blessing.~
@3659 = ~May the blessing of Eldath be with you.~
@3660 = ~Exalted Fallskeeper... why do we never carry weapons, even when others do? Isn’t peace worth defending?~
@3661 = ~Peace is not a thing we carry in our hands, but in our hearts. A blade can silence a voice—but never spread stillness.~
@3662 = ~But what if someone brings violence to our grove? What if they don’t listen?~
@3663 = ~Then we listen more. Words can reach where arrows cannot. And if they strike, we do not answer with pain, but with presence.~
@3664 = ~I don’t think I understand yet... but I will try.~
@3665 = ~Then you already walk her path. Eldath asks for no haste—only the courage not to halt. Go now, and let each step be as soft as falling rain.~
@3666 = ~Thank you for your guidance, Exalted Fallskeeper. I hope that one day I will come to understand Eldath's teachings in all her glory.~
